qas.question: What did the war do for the reputation of Frederick the Great?

answers.text: Frederick the Great’s personal reputation was enormously enhanced

qas.question: What was the general opinion of Frederick the Great military acumen?

answers.text: his military genius was strenuously kept alive

qas.question: What good fortune from Russia assisted Frederick the Great?
What gain did Russia make from the results of the war?

answers.text: Russia, on the other hand, made one great invisible gain from the war: the elimination of French influence in Poland

qas.question: What countries were party to The First Partition of Poland?

answers.text: a Russo-Prussian transaction, with Austria only reluctantly involved

context: Prussia emerged from the war as a great power whose importance could no longer be challenged. <a0_0>Frederick the Great’s personal reputation was enormously enhanced<a0_0/>, as his debt to fortune (<a2_0>Russia’s volte-face<a2_0/> after Elizabeth’s death) and to the British subsidy were soon forgotten while the memory of his energy and <a1_0>his military genius was strenuously kept alive<a1_0/>. <a3_0>Russia, on the other hand, made one great invisible gain from the war: the elimination of French influence in Poland<a3_0/>. The First Partition of Poland (1772) was to be <a4_0>a Russo-Prussian transaction, with Austria only reluctantly involved<a4_0/> and with France simply ignored.
